19901c12-3655-4d9b-82ba-3a27f1c89c79	content	<div>What a great trip you are on and what a great way to look back to the time you were married !<br><br>  Going through life with a companion whom you deeply love and are committed to is a gift and we both are thankful that the two of you have found each other . Truman, welcome to this wonderful family. I'm guessing by now, after 10 yrs, you know everyones names . Take good care of my niece, and hopefully as Carrie brings your slippers and rubs your neck daily, she will do so with the same smile Vera has always worn. Carrie, immense patience on Vera's part has been key to our success and though Truman may test you less due to his steady hand,  a little patience comes in handy. <br>           Congrats, best wishes and love ..... lets celebrate together soon !   Brian and Vera</div>	Thought	3b6dc7c2-5091-4524-adf0-6030dcd5f181	2020-10-12 12:43:14.714206	2020-10-12 12:43:14.714206
639b5037-939e-4d7f-a408-f6dbe4f56c8d	content	<div>Congrats to you both, Truman and Carrie! We are so happy for you! Enjoy each adventure together. <br>The one thing that Eric and I try to always do is use the terms "we" and "our" instead of "I" and "mine". <br>Blessings on your marriage,<br>Uncle Eric and Aunt Julie</div>	Thought	90d12d03-b88e-4455-8504-819703354731	2020-10-12 13:21:16.363916	2020-10-12 13:21:16.363916
016903e7-bdc7-46a4-8637-2fb25e5d927a	content	<div>Carrie and I learned three important things on the second day of our trip:  Oklahoma is much less flat than we thought; Oklahoma is exactly as flat as we thought; and Carrie gets mild elevation sickness. Also that we can't be bothered to look up the elevation of our airbnbs, which is I guess four things.<br><br>And fifth-ly, from one of our Bristow hosts, Bob:  Prague, Oklahoma (pronounced in perfect midwestern: PRAY-g) is home to a sizable Czech population and has a great bakery with a whole whole bunch of kolaches.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8zOTAxYjVjYS1lZmY5LTQ2YjMtOTVjYy02ZGY4Y2Q1MDY1YzM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--641abecb4c04d675f6546d76a38042694449d90b" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt6T1RBeFlqVmpZUzFsWm1ZNUxUUTJZak10T1RWall5MDJaR1k0WTJRMU1EWTFZek1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--baf0790a1f4a8ddfa1ad050588cc1b84477c058d/IMG_3015.jpg" filename="IMG_3015.jpg" filesize="192460" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="and we got some"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><h1>Oklahoma is much less flat than we thought</h1><div><br>Carrie has had a book, "one thousand things to see before you die," for quite a few years.  I think we're on thing six or thing seven, which isn't a great grade, percentage wise.  Anyway we decided to add an eighth thing: the Witchita Mountains Wildlife Refuge in central-ish Oklahoma.  It's an hour or so detour off of highway forty.<br><br>The wildlife refuge is home, in addition to the wildlife, to the Witchita Mountains' highest peak:  Mt. Scott.  It rises dramatically above the somewhat boring floor of Oklahoma to something like twenty two hundred feat.  It's a pretty neat sight:<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8wMmRkNDgzNy03ODhlLTRjZjctYjcyZC1jMDkxODUxZTRmMjM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--255f6455d4e50ebb1c26907f076fbb1fae03e341" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt3TW1Sa05EZ3pOeTAzT0RobExUUmpaamN0WWpjeVpDMWpNRGt4T0RVeFpUUm1Nak1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--c321bfa5d908f98fc4407cd738eb92e20d0ac1fb/IMG_0401.jpg" filename="IMG_0401.jpg" filesize="69303" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="Can't you tell?"></action-text-attachment><br><br>It was fairly cloudy when we arrived in the early afternoon, but it was still pretty fun to poke around inside of a cloud, looking at rocks and this juniper tree.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9lYzgxNjJlNy0yMTBjLTRlMGQtYTMwZS05OGNiZWJkODczMmQ_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--bf0fced6b93c53fcaa779c687fe3756b0195f951" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxsWXpneE5qSmxOeTB5TVRCakxUUmxNR1F0WVRNd1pTMDVPR05pWldKa09EY3pNbVFHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--4aa835b07241fe93e21ae354141a991edc7d0728/IMG_0574.jpg" filename="IMG_0574.jpg" filesize="109531" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="rocks"></action-text-attachment><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi85MTg1NDk0YS1kYTIyLTRkMjAtYWU4Ni00YWUzZDZkZWRlMTc_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--309ceca551deb578740e415358c55f70ce2c8caa" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs1TVRnMU5EazBZUzFrWVRJeUxUUmtNakF0WVdVNE5pMDBZV1V6WkRaa1pXUmxNVGNHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--483fa88673b380d4f1129ea9aca4db442e777b7d/IMG_5874.jpg" filename="IMG_5874.jpg" filesize="390077" width="640" height="853" presentation="gallery" caption="this juniper tree"></action-text-attachment><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi82MmM1ZTcwNS1jZjQ0LTQ1ZGQtOWJhNi02NTI1ZjFkMWRiMjg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--b9398776391a79c8f58bbe914bcace5529a5951c" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWsyTW1NMVpUY3dOUzFqWmpRMExUUTFaR1F0T1dKaE5pMDJOVEkxWmpGa01XUmlNamdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--5d63fba12bf03c760a6af089fd3cc52666a25909/IMG_8655.jpg" filename="IMG_8655.jpg" filesize="112835" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="this pose feels sort of like a victorian portrait"></action-text-attachment><br><br>We ended up spending like three hours here, driving around to see animals, getting out of the car to see animals, and hiking and hoping not to see (dangerous, snake-or-scorpion) animals.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi85ZjcyYWFjOC00NTcwLTRmZjgtYjYxYS1iNmY0NDRmYThkZGM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--b6fe7bab6cb34cc65ada3223178ebb58b73ac2e8" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs1WmpjeVlXRmpPQzAwTlRjd0xUUm1aamd0WWpZeFlTMWlObVkwTkRSbVlUaGtaR01HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--273b2af16a10feda405f385152c15e392dfb9a88/IMG_5405.jpg" filename="IMG_5405.jpg" filesize="145266" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="animals"></action-text-attachment><br>Most exciting -- and the single most-photographed subject of our trip -- was a section of the park marked "Prairie Dog Village" which turned out to be a <em>literal</em> prairie dog village.  We both thought it was a cutesy name for an administrative building or something until we got there.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80ZmMwNGRkYS05ZmQ1LTQzMWEtYThiMy02YmMxYjcwNjJiNDA_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--734d35ab0d8f24a6318612f33e91d8779b1d1f4f" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswWm1Nd05HUmtZUzA1Wm1RMUxUUXpNV0V0WVRoaU15MDJZbU14WWpjd05qSmlOREFHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--48514318545894fb82c11fa274431f20f70d6f95/IMG_0553.jpg" filename="IMG_0553.jpg" filesize="348370" width="640" height="853" presentation="gallery" caption="look at that thing!"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80NjgyNTcwYi1kYTc4LTRiZTgtOGVkMS00ZTAxZDk2NDdmMzc_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--e8d8d8e52ab08cadf41b5b25d1a3843536062bed" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswTmpneU5UY3dZaTFrWVRjNExUUmlaVGd0T0dWa01TMDBaVEF4WkRrMk5EZG1NemNHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--f12e720c0d20029027f5209dcd6b6c73f3a5ff8c/IMG_0669.jpg" filename="IMG_0669.jpg" filesize="191081" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="majestic!"></action-text-attachment><br><br>Finally, there were some narrowly-winding, can't-see-it-more-than-the-next-ten-feet hiking trails.  We took a short saunter (thanks, Kathleen!) and invented chants for the tall-grass areas like "rattle snakes go away, come again another day."  If that sounds familiar it's because our imagination was focused more on scary snakes than inventive counter-spells.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80MzM2MjY0MS04NDUwLTRmOTAtODhkNS0wN2NkZDk1ODczMjM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--6867d2ff06be7aa350eae38cb32e11d7661ca64b" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswTXpNMk1qWTBNUzA0TkRVd0xUUm1PVEF0T0Roa05TMHdOMk5rWkRrMU9EY3pNak1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--2e96e7505d3b85ab62fd92b95fc6ca98db3d3056/FullSizeRender.jpg" filename="FullSizeRender.jpg" filesize="77798" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="this is Carrie"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9mNjRlYjBjYy0xOTg3LTQxY2UtYTVhNS1iOWIzMzY1NWViZDM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--4789b960c064064c83ccf68acac843d9d3b40897" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxtTmpSbFlqQmpZeTB4T1RnM0xUUXhZMlV0WVRWaE5TMWlPV0l6TXpZMU5XVmlaRE1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--434986fdd6710c539b363af0b6f141006c4c6b5c/IMG_3765.jpg" filename="IMG_3765.jpg" filesize="317005" width="640" height="853" presentation="gallery" caption="this is flowers"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi85MzNlYjFhYS0yMGNjLTQwMzgtOTYxMy02N2Y5YzMzZDRiZWE_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--86369b9d29d73b412cfd4e5413bdb068ce8d39f2" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs1TXpObFlqRmhZUzB5TUdOakxUUXdNemd0T1RZeE15MDJOMlk1WXpNelpEUmlaV0VHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--bcf428816f3c747795cfaafd7505376ed24b1454/IMG_0676.jpg" filename="IMG_0676.jpg" filesize="185093" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="this is the least urban hat that Truman's coworker, Dan, has ever seen"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><h1>Oklahoma is exactly as flat as we thought</h1><div><br>I love the hills, mountains, and mesas rising around our car off in the distance, haunting the highway -- and often with spots of sun and shadow thrown around. Western Oklahoma, however, is flat.  And the top-part (I guess the "pan-handle" but what a ridiculous visual metaphor if you look at Texas on a map) of Texas is equally flat.  And the easternmost bit of New Mexico is also pretty flat, at least until it is decidedly not anymore.<br><br>And if my writing is a reflection of the beautiful and varied landscape that we're passing through, this is about all that I can say for those particular places.<br><br></div><h1>and Carrie gets mild elevation sickness</h1><div>Although flat, the eastern edge of New Mexico is one long slow climb up to Albuquerque.  Our airbnb there was actually on the eastern edge of town, up in the <a href="https://www.fs.usda.gov/cibola">Cibola National Forest</a>.  We had to do a bit of off-roading on a bumpy, winding dirt path to get to <a href="https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/19159018">Casa Canoncito</a>, which is a beautiful house tucked in the hills.<br><br>Carrie was feeling a bit off all of that day, and felt worse going in to the evening and following morning.  We found out that not only is Albuquerque higher up than Denver, we'd traveled a further thousand-or-so feet up to 6800 in what is probably the highest spot we could have picked to stay that evening.  Common wisdom for mild elevation sickness is to sleep somewhere lower.  This is not particularly helpful common wisdom for us at the time.<br><br>It was dark when we arrived -- around ten, mountain time -- so our ascent was exciting and a bit mysterious.  Before getting tucked into the hills, we could see the lights of Albuquerque spread out below, shooting off toward the horizon.  Unfortunately these views don't translate well to static pictures so you'll have to visit yourself sometime.</div>	Post	8c357e19-7a02-457f-b47e-3e5004a16769	2020-10-12 16:42:32.245123	2020-10-12 16:42:32.575614
591d92ad-b6dc-4c90-96e8-5b462160422f	content	<div>It's a beautiful night on the western edge of Arizona.  We decided to stop short of Las Vegas in Dolan Springs at an exceedingly cute camper called <a href="https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/41842849">Broken Arrow</a>.  This is one of our stops without wifi and, while I have the opportunity to catch up on these journals, you all won't be able to read them until we're safely in Wawona.  Which you're doing now.  So hello to myself in the future at Wawona -- and hello to you, I suppose from the past.  Writing in-time is pretty awkward, which is why I probably shouldn't acknowledge it.<br><br>There's a surprisingly comfortable couch outside and I wanted to write for a bit under a joshua tree, under the stars.  I walked out and settled in while Carrie took a "pre-sleep" nap in the camper.  And then I started reading about scorpions -- did you know that they're avid and capable climbers? -- and now I'm back in the small camper holding on to the fiction that we're quite safe and that the seals around the door are extra sealed.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi84ZDkyNzJkYi05NzZiLTRiNDEtYmMzZi03OWUxYjY5NGI2Njg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--358bf1bad38d692f5bbd5ac39fbe6274545725ec" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs0WkRreU56SmtZaTA1TnpaaUxUUmlOREV0WW1NelppMDNPV1V4WWpZNU5HSTJOamdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--6d2d91bb12edab70a672752f09698b61acb3c27a/62412158486__587A7049-81B1-436D-A19B-33380EAC1573%202.jpg" filename="62412158486__587A7049-81B1-436D-A19B-33380EAC1573 2.jpg" filesize="174657" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="a view from our fortress against the rising tide of darkness (scorpions)"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi81YTRkYzlmZS02NmZkLTRmYjItYWRiYS0yNWJmN2U1ZDc2Y2Y_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--0e3f40fd962cf981544fb12a7fb6db49138f32c9" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWsxWVRSa1l6bG1aUzAyTm1aa0xUUm1Zakl0WVdSaVlTMHlOV0ptTjJVMVpEYzJZMllHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--c72157da9bcae5844c5412ed69e2881c92dfa040/IMG_2758.jpg" filename="IMG_2758.jpg" filesize="53619" width="640" height="147" presentation="gallery" caption="panorama so fancy!"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><h1>Getting In A Bit Early</h1><div>After two long days and after-dark arrivals, Carrie and I decided to drive more or less straight from Albuquerque to Dolan Springs -- about seven hours.  We start our drives each day with an extremely holy ritual, which reminds me that I should mention:<br><br><strong>"500 Miles" by the Proclaimers listen count:  4.</strong><br><br>The secret is to listen through to the following track until it just begins the <em>dun dun dun dunna dunna dun dun</em> so as to feel connected continuously through the Proclaimers' earnest warbling as it exists through time, and space, and our flickering souls.  You may have thought that our coming marriage was the common thread that we pull through each of our days' experience, but I must beg to differ.  Carrie is much less enthusiastic about this idea than I am, but I'm slowly warming her up to the call-and-response <em>duh duh luh dah</em> sung throughout.  The secret, if you listen closely near the end, is the elongated beginning <em>duuuuh</em> in the final call.  It's important to get this right.<br><br>I know, also, that the song is officially titled "I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)" in case you were rushing to point that out to me.  I don't -- as a true-to-the-heart fan might say -- care.<br><br>Uh, anyway. It was a bright and beautiful morning when we set out from Casa Canoncito in Albuquerque.  Carrie soothed her stomach with oats and the almost-always-effective distraction of birds.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8yM2Y2OGVmNC01ZmI1LTRlNTYtODc5Yi1mYmNlMWU5ZmQ4NDg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--c10833d67f1a50ebf56a8b5f7456076cbde65e4a" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt5TTJZMk9HVm1OQzAxWm1JMUxUUmxOVFl0T0RjNVlpMW1ZbU5sTVdVNVptUTRORGdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--12928b7dbcb2f866ada2cc381dd4e4f69fe6b349/IMG_2441.jpg" filename="IMG_2441.jpg" filesize="154819" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="playing the age old &quot;where'd that bird go?!&quot; game"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80YzVjYTIwMi04NjlmLTQyMzUtOWYyZS05MDJmM2U4YmNjZWM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--2156b5aabe62741de1a1dec8a94f901a30891741" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswWXpWallUSXdNaTA0TmpsbUxUUXlNelV0T1dZeVpTMDVNREptTTJVNFltTmpaV01HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--0c99b301a6e57ca47b2762866f9642704d91be70/IMG_0605.jpg" filename="IMG_0605.jpg" filesize="198187" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="the wild hills of Albuquerque"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><h1>Flagstaff</h1><div><br>We were about thirty minutes into our journey when Bryan, our incredibly kind Albuquerque host, messaged to let us know that we'd forgotten a titanium spork (this is a real thing that we own) in their sink.  Bryan offered to mail it ahead to us, but we figured the timing wouldn't work too well and donated it to their household instead.  Fortunately there's an REI in Flagstaff and we figured we'd drop by, and so set out on the highway.<br><br>"In 1000 feet, merge onto highway 40.  Continue for four hundred sixty miles."  Thanks for the heads-up on what we're doing today, map robot.<br><br>Although I don't really want to live in the southwest -- and for more reasons than the threat of glow-under-blacklight (so terrifying!) scorpions -- I love the scenery as we're driving.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8yYTI5N2EzYS04Nzk3LTQ5NzctYTgyNy03YmNkYWJiYTUwN2E_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--5ba171a3b4a703842f707a7d3472afcab830600f" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt5WVRJNU4yRXpZUzA0TnprM0xUUTVOemN0WVRneU55MDNZbU5rWVdKaVlUVXdOMkVHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--d659c92bddb5df84a19050cc95c41832951dd4de/IMG_2754.jpg" filename="IMG_2754.jpg" filesize="80615" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="okay it's hard to tell but this is actually extremely beautiful"></action-text-attachment><br><br>Flagstaff was neat; we purchased a new titanium spork for backpack eating, bought a loaf of Dave's Killer Bread for on-the-road sandwiches (review:  good sandwich bread, but killer?  I may be showing my colors as a bread snob when I say "no."), and met a woman that grew up in Downer's Grove.  It may be a small world, but our time in the car is indicating otherwise to Carrie and I.<br><br></div><h1>Loose Cows</h1><div><br>It was still light out as Carrie and I trundled in to Dolan Springs.  A sign on the side of the road advised to keep on the lookout for "loose cows" in the road.  Shortly after, the Rugged Prius began emitting a familiar scraping noise.  I should mention at this point that between Chicago streets' speed humps and our sometimes inattention while driving quickly over Chicago streets' speed humps, our car's undercarriage was in rough shape.  There's a large plastic shield down there that is currently held on with a collection of zip-ties.<br><br>This would mark the second time in our trip that we had to cut off a section of the plastic that had dipped too low.  And so with a collection of loose cows looking onward, I got down in the dust with our small pocket knife and sawed off another bit of the car.<br><br></div><h1>Broken Arrow</h1><div><br>We were grateful to arrive at Broken Arrow with plenty of light left and enjoyed an evening that was several times longer, and many times more relaxing, than the fall-into-bed-fall-out-of-bed-into-the-car nights we'd enjoyed for the past few nights.  The desert is gorgeous, and the stars are gorgeous, and the scorpions are terrifying.  I'm watching you, tiny terrorbugs.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9lNWNkM2NmNy01NDQzLTQyZTItYTYzZS1kNWQwMjQ5YjdhNGM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--7f4a3a5946791317df086162515d80262ded5a21" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxsTldOa00yTm1OeTAxTkRRekxUUXlaVEl0WVRZelpTMWtOV1F3TWpRNVlqZGhOR01HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--ce747e6cb1eaca1ce4a1af1bfe5baad41e8f3766/IMG_2763.jpg" filename="IMG_2763.jpg" filesize="139219" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="behind these smiling faces are the battle-sharpened minds of scorpion hunting warriors"></action-text-attachment></div>	Post	fadbc165-eb4b-4c5f-91df-b2d231661b78	2020-10-12 16:58:17.199527	2020-10-12 16:58:17.832314
ebeda627-1f8e-46f8-be70-29b6cac97696	content	<div>Dearest Carrie and Truman,<br> <br>In typical fashion, we didn't see your requests for letters until the day before your journey to the mountaintop. Needless to say I would have much rather written something by hand, but I think you will agree this is much more my style. <br><br>Words cannot describe how happy we were when you guys told us you were getting married. Having known you both for so long, having known your stories, this is the perfect beginning to your next chapter. Many more adventures await, through many more trials, and many more triumphs.<br><br>It's a simple thing you are doing - affirming something you both already know. It's a simple act, with a bare minimum of two words to get the job done. But that simple act is chock full of meaning, filled to overflowing with love, of trust in each other, and commitment to something greater than the sum of its parts. <br><br>I'm only saying all this gushy stuff to point out something else you both already know. This is something worth celebrating. This is one of the payoffs for the love you share, the commitment you have given each other. You've made it to the top of the mountain! I'm sure you can see the many other peaks you may climb someday, but for now, enjoy the view. Enjoy each other- this day is for you. <br><br>With all the love we can muster, <br><br>Ben and Allison<br><br>P.s. Dear Catballs,<br><br>Bark, Bark. Woof! <br><br>Kindest Regards,<br>Olly</div>	Thought	24270cc0-121b-4410-8b19-e338a4d22a93	2020-10-12 19:46:48.474194	2020-10-12 19:46:48.474194
d3ba46d5-4890-4800-afad-9d3413d4a058	content	<div>After reading your journal up through Dolan Springs, I wanted to remind Carrie of the altitude sickness she and Matt got in Breckenridge many years ago.  Sounds like she is still bothered.  The solution is water, water water! Drink twice what you think you need.  Yosemite will be a struggle if you don't stay hydrated.  Hope that is helpful and you both have a lovely wedding day with no altitude sickness!</div>	Thought	fc610a12-be72-43b7-8332-353904f78d0c	2020-10-12 19:51:17.410117	2020-10-12 19:51:17.410117
4091cc44-ad74-45a2-a597-45ffd7e4ba87	content	<div><em>Dear Truman and Carrie, <br><br>I wish you a lifetime of love and happiness!<br><br>Love,  Grandma Shuck </em></div>	Thought	ff57e870-079c-49c4-9f43-ea1fa4ccebaf	2020-10-12 20:50:10.532202	2020-10-12 20:50:10.532202
e8af4190-0a93-4e98-809c-1dfbf9a8a33c	content	<div>Dear Carrie and Truman! <br><br>Best wishes for a wonderful marriage.  No advice from me (smile) but a world of support.  Enjoy your wonderful trip! Hope to see you soon.<br><br>Love, Aunt Bev</div>	Thought	14355bf8-573f-49ae-b74c-0f40ed52bfad	2020-10-12 20:54:47.669112	2020-10-12 20:54:47.669112
37710b56-221e-46de-8286-ea31edb8d47a	content	<div>Hi Carrie and Truman!<br><br>I thoroughly enjoyed reading your journal just now and look forward to other entries.  Love your writing Truman!<br>I am totally with you about the scorpions!  They, along with other undesirable spiders lurk here in Austin.  They better never enter this house or, frankly, my path!  I am not equipped to deal with it.<br><br>I love that everything about your trip and plans you have made so special.<br>Bill and I wish you every happiness and appreciate being able to share in your celebration/adventure through this journal.<br><br>Sending love and early congratulations for tomorrow's big day!<br><br><br></div>	Thought	ac86210e-c9cc-4933-9e3c-adad4bc1495e	2020-10-12 22:42:57.731063	2020-10-12 22:42:57.731063
b816485e-4c25-4c20-8d1e-a061609fb1cb	content	<div>Love you both! Here's a poem!<br><br><br>If loving a person was all you could do<br><br>The ocean is blue because the sky is blue<br><br>The plants of the earth sway to their truth<br><br>A beckoning motion that's calling for you<br><br>If you had a girl that was falling for you<br><br>You'd cradle her head when she's feeling blue<br><br>You'd tell her real sweetly, 'I've been waiting for you,<br><br>the hand, the ocean, the sky, and the truth'<br><br>You'd see behind windows the man is a boy<br><br>A sweetly serious, goofy boy<br><br>'Waiting for you, I've been waiting for you<br><br>Drifting in water 'til you swam through'<br><br>A lone lost wild singing refrain<br><br>'What is your name' again and again<br><br>And seeing you sitting upon a pine log<br><br>Hoping to god that you're not a frog<br><br>If loving a person was all you could do<br><br>I'd wish in this world there was only you<br><br>The ocean, the grasslands, the mountains, the blue<br><br>Are all for each other <br><br>I am for you</div>	Thought	1348798a-ee4b-4d91-b1a7-aa7aceafd2df	2020-10-13 13:03:49.748602	2020-10-13 13:03:49.748602
f5a91d2e-f1ff-4a68-93fb-af9b4aecfdcd	content	<div>My goodness, Carrie and Truman, what a great way to get married and have a wonderful trip of a lifetime, one of many in your future I hope!  Just think, if you were to have an encounter with a scorpion how much more impactful your honeymoon memories would be!  Ten years together, and from what I have seen, each of you has grown into mature, interesting, and interested individuals better together than apart. I wish you happiness and wonderful memories to nuture you and grow your relationship.  XXOOO   Love your writing, Truman</div>	Thought	2f267c92-3595-4ea2-ac79-1b26161f5db0	2020-10-13 22:59:46.428703	2020-10-13 22:59:46.428703
b779b972-5162-4581-9aba-0496172fa881	content	<div>Congrats Carrie &amp; Truman! <br><br>Becca and I wish you both a lifetime of happiness together. May this trip be the first of many great memories to come! It's been a joy following your journey from afar—know that we are 100% living vicariously through you from our tiny children filled bubble in Chicago. It probably goes without saying, but enjoy the rest of your trip and travel safe. <br><br>Your friends,<br><br>The Lavin's<br><br>P.S. I look forward to more updates—particularly ones that include your wonderful urban hat. </div>	Thought	3e258d8f-ffda-4f97-b3eb-715f7ecc95b8	2020-10-14 03:46:50.121091	2020-10-14 03:46:50.121091
af569386-131c-45cd-83ca-10e227de1db7	content	<div>Carrie and Truman, Congratulations to you on finally tying the knot!  I hope the day was both fun and stress free (and with a settled stomach)! I am dying here waiting for photos and your journal entries!!! No pressure but get on it!  I love you both and I LOVE Jefferson's poem!</div>	Thought	07f9aef0-3a63-4e3e-9076-4247cd8b2494	2020-10-14 15:52:54.812063	2020-10-14 15:52:54.812063
3d1bbd8a-dd6d-4d4a-b9bc-5026b82dad60	content	<h1>Yosemite</h1><div><br>So it's almost, in this journal-zone, time to get married.  But on Monday, October 12th, we had some errands to run:  getting our marriage license, and picking up dinner.<br><br></div><div>We'd called a bunch of the counties surrounding Yosemite in late August to see if any were granting marriage licenses -- none were, at the time:  they were closed on that Monday, or hadn't started scheduling for October, or were only seeing county residents.  San Francisco was doing virtual licenses, but you had to be in the state for the video call.  So short of hanging up a poster of the golden gate behind us ("oh yeah we sure love living in California where we definitely are right now!"), it didn't seem likely that we'd be legally married.</div><div><br>I called a few of those folks back in the week leading up to our departure -- and Madera county would grant ours!  We were pretty excited, both because it seemed more official, and especially because it would save us two trips to the courthouse in Chicago sometime later.  It looks like Carrie's big wedding pitch --  cheaper healthcare, cheaper taxes -- was going to pay off.<br><br>We drove out of Yosemite on Monday morning and into Madera, CA.  I spent at least a few words talking up Tioga Pass in the prior post, but I'll do so again.  The western entrance to Yosemite is fine, but it's nothing compared to the views coming in from the east.<br><br></div><h1>One Star Reviews</h1><div><br>There's a pretty hilarious series of "<a href="https://www.boredpanda.com/one-star-reviews-into-illustrations-national-parks-amber-share">one-star national parks reviews</a>" from folks who couldn't quite see the grandeur of some of America's most beautiful places.  I think Yosemite is a solid five-star from both Carrie and I, but our one-star review would be:  "Roads are way too winding.  Lots of dust on the trails.  Trees all look the same."<br><br></div><h1>Last Bits</h1><div><br>I'm writing this post because this journal serves the retrospective purpose of reminding us what our trip was like.  I want to write the following post, and it's getting late -- 11:45pm in Lone Pine on Wednesday, October 14th -- so here's the rest in bullet form:<br><br>  - A kind government worker granted Carrie and I our marriage license (we'd just have to track down a witness day-of)<br>  - We ate at Sal's Mexican Restaurant in Madera (I got a <em>fancy</em> burrito, every single item on Carrie's plate was covered in cheese)<br>  - We visited Raley's grocery store in Oakhurst, CA, and bought chevre, crackers, grapes, and prosciutto for post-ceremony breakfast, as well as some chicken for wedding dinner.<br><br></div><h1>That's it</h1><div><br></div><div>We didn't really take any pictures today because we were mostly just running around getting ready for our big day on Tuesday.  Hopefully I'll go write that post now! </div>	Post	8a499ee3-7c77-4abb-93c8-fa779ac28321	2020-10-15 06:45:11.54657	2020-10-15 06:45:11.54657
bec09979-fce7-4c5c-8f52-c9be009c457d	content	<h1>I mean "high point" literally:  Tioga Pass</h1><div><br>I know it's now Wednesday, which means that Carrie and I have been married for just over twenty four hours, and that's presumably the more important thing that I could post about, but I'm not going to break up the order of my posts.  I'm a principled documentarian.<br><br></div><h1>Leaving Broken Arrow</h1><div><br>I cannot stress how cute this camper is.  Also although it's almost literally in the middle of nowhere, it was the best-furnished (sans wifi) spot so far on our trip:  a real freezer (where we can refreeze our icepacks), and a real stove upon which we can make breakfast!<br> <action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8xMmY4YzE4ZS0yZDk4LTRiZjYtOGRhNS03NmU4MDAyNzVmYTg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--c160ec866f44edc66162257e4480e58384f6cf16" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt4TW1ZNFl6RTRaUzB5WkRrNExUUmlaall0T0dSaE5TMDNObVU0TURBeU56Vm1ZVGdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--5017db0a255cc3949d1758223256a78ff463e1d1/IMG_2782%202.jpg" filename="IMG_2782 2.jpg" filesize="165910" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="ask for glamorous hat pictures and ye shall receive"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><div><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9jNmI1ZGI3OC05NDg2LTQ2ZjAtOGRhYi1mMGMwMWZkZjMxYTY_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--3ef09deacc3fca9271ae3eccc0c9acc5b656b87c" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxqTm1JMVpHSTNPQzA1TkRnMkxUUTJaakF0T0dSaFlpMW1NR013TVdaa1pqTXhZVFlHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--50aca5915bbd412a94551cbd95a35c881620faa4/IMG_2784.jpg" filename="IMG_2784.jpg" filesize="145032" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="oh and Carrie is here too"></action-text-attachment><br><br>I forgot to mention that Carrie's first act upon driving in to Dolan Springs was to promptly hit a road runner.  To be fair, it did dart from the side of the road directly at our car.  Apparently it did a comical looney tunes spin and ran back into the brush, so it's probably alright.  I didn't see it because I was focused on the car ahead that had slowed down suddenly -- at which we were still barreling toward.  Fortunately everyone -- except perhaps the bird -- remains fine.<br><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80YTUzYTdhNC0wNWQxLTRlMmMtYTM0My1iYjA3MWQyZDFiNzE_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--182cf17542a261f18408fe7e16c89ca95e7505ba" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswWVRVellUZGhOQzB3TldReExUUmxNbU10WVRNME15MWlZakEzTVdReVpERmlOekVHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--895ef621c2b6c7ffe63d3e9f62995dd053820e64/62412354950__A6EE936B-15EE-4A12-BA70-F151016A86F1%202.jpg" filename="62412354950__A6EE936B-15EE-4A12-BA70-F151016A86F1 2.jpg" filesize="132665" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="rest in peace, little buddy (because you're still alive and comfortably napping somewhere out in the brush)"></action-text-attachment><br><br></div><h1>Driving to Yosemite</h1><div><br>This has been my favorite drive of the trip.  The land in Nevada stretches away to mountains as you drive along the California border.  It's gigantic and beautiful.  Also we've learned that Carrie may have slight agoraphobia -- she seems to get a bit antsy as we travel in wide, wide, wide open spaces with only sometimes another car in sight.  We'll see what this means for Death Valley in a few days!<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80NzRhZTJjYi1hNzY4LTRkOTAtYmEyMC1iMDI4YzljNTIwM2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--ac4b089e984573ef8df1f1ecac578cf97d259664" content-type="image/png" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswTnpSaFpUSmpZaTFoTnpZNExUUmtPVEF0WW1FeU1DMWlNREk0WXpsak5USXdNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--65969e5d25f91455559b1df8c96ff47e5167a34a/Screen%20Shot%202020-10-14%20at%209.35.10%20AM.png" filename="Screen Shot 2020-10-14 at 9.35.10 AM.png" filesize="349706" width="640" height="375" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="the road through Tioga Pass (northwest corner)"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9kY2MwYWJmZS1lMDU4LTQ0YzktOGM3OS1jMjhlMjUzYTQ2ODg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--58601d8f9ea62013d29750a37d6fdd5153292abf" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxrWTJNd1lXSm1aUzFsTURVNExUUTBZemt0T0dNM09TMWpNamhsTWpVellUUTJPRGdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--b722c8ca483a04ae176b484bedc63c75a31a7a0d/IMG_2334.jpg" filename="IMG_2334.jpg" filesize="89158" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="mountains and one tree"></action-text-attachment><br><br>We also stopped off at the Hoover Dam, but the dam itself is closed.  We did get to drive up to this overlook of Lake Mead, which is created by the dam.  Also even the gas stations as we start ascending are beautiful.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi85NTMyMGY4My1mMThjLTRjY2EtYjliOC01YzI0NmRjZWYwOGM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--b10fd1492cb431e015333a8f1917e06e5c0dce67" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs1TlRNeU1HWTRNeTFtTVRoakxUUmpZMkV0WWpsaU9DMDFZekkwTm1SalpXWXdPR01HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--f6f84362a1792bf77a340cd867250d5de9482365/IMG_2786%202.jpg" filename="IMG_2786 2.jpg" filesize="143465" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="we couldn't see the dam, but the view was nice"></action-text-attachment><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8zMDFkNmFjZi0zMTBlLTRhNzYtOTNkZi0yYjJhMjFhYjExNWM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--8d91ec8712e9891afdc31d17761252573f719a6d" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt6TURGa05tRmpaaTB6TVRCbExUUmhOell0T1ROa1ppMHlZakpoTWpGaFlqRXhOV01HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--e9f1ae5f1bb8e75bca9b36de88129267c1c1252a/IMG_2791.jpg" filename="IMG_2791.jpg" filesize="135340" width="640" height="480" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="nice gas station"></action-text-attachment><br><br><br></div><h1>Tioga Pass</h1><div>The drive up to Tioga Pass is incredible.  We drove through scrub, forests and near water through the elevation changes.  There's one section of road on highway 120 that warns "Dips:  Next 5 Miles" which turns the car into a not-so-short rollercoaster.  Also we saw three wild horses ambling around the side of the road.  No pictures can do this area justice, but here they are nonetheless.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZ