300eac66-d945-49b4-b27f-781f8f826aa8	content	<h1>Here's the thing about hiking downward</h1><div><br>It's sort of hard.  We decided to take the recommended route to the bottom:  the South Kaibab trail.  It's a little over seven miles, pretty much all in the sun, a bit steeper than the other south rim trail, and there's no water along the way.  This doesn't exactly make it a nice trail, but since it's supposed to take twice as long to hike up, it's a much better downward trail than an upward trail.  And anyway it's still a very nice trail, and it's breathtaking -- like we're discovering most of the west to be.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi83ZmE2MGY4YS00NzA3LTQ3NjMtYTdlNS00MmNlYTBhYzI5M2Y_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--7636a90c0247e33ec573d5ebd8791f27b8c283d9" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWszWm1FMk1HWTRZUzAwTnpBM0xUUTNOak10WVRkbE5TMDBNbU5sWVRCaFl6STVNMllHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--0f14253ef263d202cb5f9f961bdedffcf02b662e/IMG_3235.jpeg" filename="IMG_3235.jpeg" filesize="142368" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="here we are at the top, unsuspecting smiles and fresh faces"></action-text-attachment><br><br>We breakfasted on egg burritos and potatoes and hopped a shuttle to the trailhead -- it's about two miles away, and we were able to leave the Rugged Prius nearer to the return trail so that we would not have to walk further after walking forever already.  We never found a place to weigh our packs, but they were sort of heavy, especially with the four-ish liters of water that we packed along.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi84ZjJhN2Q4Ny1mNzI5LTQ3ZWQtYjUzZC1lNGU5ZWQxYmMzM2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--1bb3e4bfc51f1a5a3d8a5a520267343c4f633d8f" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs0WmpKaE4yUTROeTFtTnpJNUxUUTNaV1F0WWpVelpDMWxOR1U1WldReFltTXpNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--cf1530a7c68661986a68792c0c32a73063454306/IMG_3250.jpeg" filename="IMG_3250.jpeg" filesize="131630" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="down in the canyon maybe 1000 feet"></action-text-attachment><br><br>We took a lot of pictures of the canyons which I will spare you from in the tiny-view of our journal.  We'll see about organizing the full-sized pictures from our trip somewhere nice after we get home.  There's also an option of taking a mule train down (or up), but the advice is that you'll still be pretty sore from riding mules all day so you may as well walk.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9hYWQzYTU2ZC1hNzYxLTQ0NzYtYWE1MS0wODBiZTY4ZTU2ZDI_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--8da6b7527c3418d44c848bdfd7d3b7b863a0d4a3" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxoWVdRellUVTJaQzFoTnpZeExUUTBOell0WVdFMU1TMHdPREJpWlRZNFpUVTJaRElHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--953a06092884f01944237aa68e4db034dc726313/IMG_3240.jpeg" filename="IMG_3240.jpeg" filesize="184522" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="mules always have the right-of-way"></action-text-attachment><br><br>There are a few rest stops on the way down the South Kaibab trail, complete with bathrooms.  They are surprisingly clean, and meant that we never had to dig a "cat hole" and practice our aim.  As a ranger put it later, the Grand Canyon hike is one of the more "front-country, back-country trails."  I was very grateful for this, although we still felt reasonably rugged.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9mZmMwZmQxZC00YWU4LTRhNWQtYTgzNC05OGZlNzczZDliM2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--6381d7af156321ca6b103fda4a924905098e709c" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxtWm1Nd1ptUXhaQzAwWVdVNExUUmhOV1F0WVRnek5DMDVPR1psTnpjelpEbGlNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--847b7d5edbfc2d868e3b75307b3037795df368b4/IMG_3254.jpeg" filename="IMG_3254.jpeg" filesize="114770" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="mules also need a break sometimes"></action-text-attachment><br><br>We followed the sage advice to rest often -- about ten minutes out of every hour.  We also started each morning at an "agonizingly slow" pace (more advice that Carrie found on the internet) for a half-hour, and stretched before continuing.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9lYjdmZmE4MC1kYjQ0LTQ4NDEtYWVkMC0zMzVhNDNjYTRkNzM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--f3770a5ac5c8a9eda5723bdb7823d0d1633a34bb" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxsWWpkbVptRTRNQzFrWWpRMExUUTROREV0WVdWa01DMHpNelZoTkROallUUmtOek1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--68f91d8c0b9ad2f6b3e3beda7a626d9d2b2d4c11/IMG_3272.jpeg" filename="IMG_3272.jpeg" filesize="145005" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="not this kind of stretching, but we did that too"></action-text-attachment><br><br>The views were incredible.  It's one thing to see the canyon laid out before you at the rim, but it's hard to grasp how big it is until you're down inside of it.  Trekking poles help a ton to save your knees on the descent.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9jM2RiMmI0YS0xY2FkLTQyMTMtYjVkOC1kZmFkOGYwMGVkMmM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--bdf02520bbaf881e720a2e434d298913e8eb56e9" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxqTTJSaU1tSTBZUzB4WTJGa0xUUXlNVE10WWpWa09DMWtabUZrT0dZd01HVmtNbU1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--8327a8b5686752f6837e348af32a6604c4cfe3cf/IMG_3289.jpeg" filename="IMG_3289.jpeg" filesize="181294" width="640" height="853" presentation="gallery" caption="they also make you look super cool"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi84ZDE5MWQzNi01ZjcwLTQ0ZWItOGZhYS1iMmUxZTE5MTBlYmU_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--c4382b68b446ed4b55581fc18dbc5c1c51ab256d" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs0WkRFNU1XUXpOaTAxWmpjd0xUUTBaV0l0T0daaFlTMWlNbVV4WlRFNU1UQmxZbVVHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--3296653c4cee7a0c44228e78a2296b471e29a6f3/IMG_3260.jpeg" filename="IMG_3260.jpeg" filesize="86043" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="especially in portrait mode"></action-text-attachment><br><br>The colors -- rock and vegetation -- change a ton as you descend.  Apparently you walk through <a href="https://www.dothecanyon.com/life-zones-its-founder-and-the-grand-canyon/">several life zones</a> on the way down.  There's a lot of red, brown, and black, but also a ton of greenery.  Also some lizards and an absurd number of ominously-cawing ravens.  Advice about the hike stresses eating, drinking, and resting enough, and notes that "some may finish their Grand Canyon hike and swear to never backpack again -- however many folks, including older people and tiny babies, have made it in and out with no problem.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi82NzA2YWIzYy0zN2MxLTQ1YjMtYTZkZC05ZTM0Y2YzYTZhZTY_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--6786cc27004d8d03077501ae47c79b7ff6f05c46" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWsyTnpBMllXSXpZeTB6TjJNeExUUTFZak10WVRaa1pDMDVaVE0wWTJZellUWmhaVFlHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--7a2b76fbc08ea24bff1f1752e4ad4e13f906d3cf/IMG_3274.jpeg" filename="IMG_3274.jpeg" filesize="127685" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="one of the rest stops with a composting bathroom"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8zY2JhM2ZhNy03OTg1LTRkMDEtOTM2MS1lNGE3ZjIzMGE3N2Q_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--882a92089092cb4dda7f5ca486e628275589c4f6" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt6WTJKaE0yWmhOeTAzT1RnMUxUUmtNREV0T1RNMk1TMWxOR0UzWmpJek1HRTNOMlFHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--885bd9c34c53cdbd07a023fc9684cb72ec002320/IMG_3262.jpeg" filename="IMG_3262.jpeg" filesize="155066" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="we put electrolyte tablets in our water to avoid dying of too much water (bottles from Elisa and Bob's beautiful &quot;three day festival of love&quot;)"></action-text-attachment></div><div><br></div><h1>Nearing The Bottom</h1><div><br>Eventually the Colorado River came into view.  It seemed like we were very close, but really it was like another hour or so.  There were a good number of folks on the trail, although many fewer after about the halfway point -- where it's recommended that day-trip hikers turn around and head back up.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9mN2MwNTZlMi0yM2U0LTQ1NGMtODUxYS1hZTc1YmMzYzE2OTM_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--e784d3ccebaaa00c818a40784679c49dc33df5b4" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxtTjJNd05UWmxNaTB5TTJVMExUUTFOR010T0RVeFlTMWhaVGMxWW1Nell6RTJPVE1HT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--9737e63bfefc759ab3b59cc31b9ecae805abb464/IMG_3286.jpeg" filename="IMG_3286.jpeg" filesize="134293" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="so close!"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi82MzBjMGQyMi05Y2E0LTQyNDYtYWJhNi02NmJjZWExZjBhOGE_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--0147042750e9b604849795066d3766462b14a153" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWsyTXpCak1HUXlNaTA1WTJFMExUUXlORFl0WVdKaE5pMDJObUpqWldFeFpqQmhPR0VHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--30cb3943aecd8772a050eb8681e22903c8289043/IMG_3293.jpeg" filename="IMG_3293.jpeg" filesize="182763" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="lots and lots of switchbacks"></action-text-attachment><br><br>Near the end of the trail is the Black Bridge, which crosses the Colorado maybe half of a mile before the campsite.  The hiking map warns not to swim in the Colorado because it's wide and swift, and I lost enough family members playing the Oregon Trail game to know not to take chances.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9jNmU2NWEzNi01NmU3LTQzODItOWE1Zi04MjE5NDM5MDE5M2I_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--1d3b51d1754e9e15fe4a04f2b4b764af2f9ecdb3" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxqTm1VMk5XRXpOaTAxTm1VM0xUUXpPREl0T1dFMVppMDRNakU1TkRNNU1ERTVNMklHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--55ca78666352f7c2f8a5257eea816a96a3d27534/IMG_3295.jpeg" filename="IMG_3295.jpeg" filesize="124917" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="a grand river for a grand canyon"></action-text-attachment><br><br>However you can raft and boat the river; we saw some folks putting in as we were finally crossing the Black Bridge.  We set off from the trailhead at around 8:30am and arrive at 2:30pm; a pace a little above one mile per hour.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi84MWJmYWZjOC1lM2ZmLTQ4YjgtYmQ1MC1kOTViMGViYTVkNzg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--6172bda8f5cd388802aac43f51a45b52ec1becbb" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWs0TVdKbVlXWmpPQzFsTTJabUxUUTRZamd0WW1RMU1DMWtPVFZpTUdWaVlUVmtOemdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--fde6f70a0e4794323c9e60682204d713c8232bb7/IMG_3296.jpeg" filename="IMG_3296.jpeg" filesize="132973" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="lucky boaters"></action-text-attachment><br><br>At the bottom are both the Bright Angel Campground, where we stayed, as well as <a href="https://www.grandcanyonlodges.com/lodging/phantom-ranch/">Phantom Ranch</a>, the only lodge at the bottom of the canyon.  After arriving, we set up camp and wandered around a bit to check out the river and the ranch.  We also saw a mom and baby mule deer crossing another small bridge over the Bright Angel creek on our way to the river.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8wN2U5YTU1Ny0xZGZkLTQ2YzgtODM0OS1kOGU2ZTRjNDY1MzE_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--8e7cff2ec9578502e7f84998cef0aea10a24c531" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt3TjJVNVlUVTFOeTB4Wkdaa0xUUTJZemd0T0RNME9TMWtPR1UyWlRSak5EWTFNekVHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--a670d35eb4ebb65d60d7d3eba31a0a5ae6bc49c8/IMG_3301.jpeg" filename="IMG_3301.jpeg" filesize="186758" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="The mom crosses the bridge, the baby decides to off-road and hopped down the small ledge to cross the hard way."></action-text-attachment><br><br>We got a bit of video of the baby crossing; both Carrie and I feared for its life, but it made it out okay (you can hear the tiny deer bleating for its mom in the video which perhaps we'll find a place to put online someday).  There's a bend where the river calms and we went and put our feet in for a bit.  It's extremely cold, although the air at the bottom of the canyon is about twenty degrees warmer than at the top -- about 90 degrees and 70 degrees when we went down.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi8zNmJhMmQ5OC01ZDJjLTQ4NjMtYjAwMC0xNDhiNzRmOGYxNTA_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--658d043b0e9ea8b85da59b7c4f7bcffdfd0fb649" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWt6Tm1KaE1tUTVPQzAxWkRKakxUUTROak10WWpBd01DMHhORGhpTnpSbU9HWXhOVEFHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--d1bbc50cb4ba148c7e0422144d2a69e06b7707f9/IMG_3303.jpeg" filename="IMG_3303.jpeg" filesize="95383" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="deceivingly placid -- what dark secrets does it hide?  (scorpions?!)"></action-text-attachment><br><br>Phantom Ranch also sells dinner and runs a small canteen.  Carrie and I were able to snag a meal of vegetable chili (plus salad, cornbread, and a small desert), which was extremely worth it.  We packed plenty of food, but it was nice not to have to heat up our backpacking ramen until the next day.  We fell asleep in our small backpacking tent exhausted after taking some time to watch the stars.  Carrie would lie awake for a few minutes during the night each time she woke up (thankfully not to the amorous sounds of nearby burros as in death valley) to admire the sky -- and saw three or four shooting stars.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9jMmFmODkyZS05YzUzLTQxMDktYTZhZi05OGY2ZTAxYjZhM2Y_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--4cff9409d1e6c4647d3def6526a099801bb79cd0" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxqTW1GbU9Ea3laUzA1WXpVekxUUXhNRGt0WVRaaFppMDVPR1kyWlRBeFlqWmhNMllHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--2a8f1f2fd0832088b250d78377cc4136e6e91d35/IMG_3307.jpeg" filename="IMG_3307.jpeg" filesize="40629" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="a bug tried to join us for dinner with a seat on Carrie's face."></action-text-attachment><br><br></div>	Post	7dc71f10-cc6c-49b0-b57e-38d496e3c2d4	2020-10-23 04:59:34.476855	2020-10-23 04:59:37.107275
8e844464-d4d5-4bc5-91da-11d876f688a1	content	<h1>Around Camp</h1><div><br>Our second day in the Grand Canyon had us hiking about halfway out via the Bright Angel Trail to a campground at Indian Garden.  Bright Angel is the suggested outbound trail because it features potable water, shade, and the mid-way stopping point.  Although we had about five miles to hike, we only had about 1300 feet of elevation that day and so didn't feel too rushed getting out of our camp.  Carrie took some time to walk back over to Phantom Ranch to check it out in the morning light, grab a few more trail snacks, and a postcard.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9kNDEyODBmYy1jMjZkLTRmMGEtODU0OS1lOTE3ZGMyOTJjZTg_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--af45b2d0aa5564a267d8709ddd825a35980ad36a" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxrTkRFeU9EQm1ZeTFqTWpaa0xUUm1NR0V0T0RVME9TMWxPVEUzWkdNeU9USmpaVGdHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--d38f6182ec8cf923780286d4c8be2d020b2c4f6b/IMG_3313.jpeg" filename="IMG_3313.jpeg" filesize="169994" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="our sweet Bright Angel camp"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9kNjlmMWNmYS0xZDQ1LTRhZDktYTEyYi0yOWY1NTZhZTcyYWI_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--a2e3baef934dff47964c26db5cf9a7490135d28f" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxrTmpsbU1XTm1ZUzB4WkRRMUxUUmhaRGt0WVRFeVlpMHlPV1kxTlRaaFpUY3lZV0lHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--5e22ef6c705fc41dae4aed9500c575377ba2df72/IMG_3317.jpg" filename="IMG_3317.jpg" filesize="85977" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="the Rugged Truman"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi80MWIyMzhhMi1hNjE0LTQ1N2QtOWZlZC01MjZlMjU2ZjljMTU_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--7bf6bdcc14f3d3192cd569ad525bf916706b1870" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWswTVdJeU16aGhNaTFoTmpFMExUUTFOMlF0T1dabFpDMDFNalpsTWpVMlpqbGpNVFVHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--1d29640f4c58a48c3f58c43d520f250c9e644b50/IMG_3319.jpeg" filename="IMG_3319.jpeg" filesize="152901" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="Phantom Ranch canteen"></action-text-attachment><br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmFnZTo6QmxvYi9kMTRkZjNhZi1lZDMzLTQ0YzItYTg3YS03OTJjODAzN2M2NjY_ZXhwaXJlc19pbgY7AFRJIgxwdXJwb3NlBjsAVEkiD2F0dGFjaGFibGUGOwBUSSIPZXhwaXJlc19hdAY7AFQw--4821657fc9f77ff8f41883d33da29a97c1947186" content-type="image/jpeg" url="https://www.carrie-truman.fyi/rails/active_storage/blobs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaEpJaWxrTVRSa1pqTmhaaTFsWkRNekxUUTBZekl0WVRnM1lTMDNPVEpqT0RBek4yTTJOallHT2daRlZBPT0iLCJleHAiOm51bGwsInB1ciI6ImJsb2JfaWQifX0=--57d263190cd3fab837d13927b287f08aa0a4fc33/IMG_3323.jpeg" filename="IMG_3323.jpeg" filesize="194328" width="640" height="480" presentation="gallery" caption="Phantom Ranch cute cottages"></action-text-attachment><br><br>The first mile-and-a-half of the Bright Angel Trail follows the Colorado River and, although there are some small ups and downs, has almost no total elevation gain.  It starts by crossing the river, and it may have been my favorite hike both for the view and because both of our legs were pretty stiff after the previous day's descent.<br><br><action-text-attachment sgid="BAh7CEkiCGdpZAY6BkVUSSJXZ2lkOi8vYW4tZXZlbnQvQWN0aXZlU3RvcmF